    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Dorsally flattened with eight shell plates articulating on its dorsal side, surrounded by a soft fleshy girdle. Girdle wide bearing fine spicules on the top, some longer, smooth spines close to the margin, as well as smooth, oviform, imbricating scales on the bottom. Shell plates broadly rectangular. Middle plates sharpen to the hind margin. Texture of shell minutely granulose with 6-7 longitudinal grooves on either side of the central area. Dark spots (shell eyes) closely set on the head valve, the side areas and the posterior area of the tail valve. Colour red, sometimes with white or cream blotches.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_6085",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Medium, typically around 5-17 mm total body length.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_6086",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> False Bay to Algoa Bay.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_6087",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Found in the subtidal zone (15-18m) in between and under stones or reefs.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_6088",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Herbivorous â€“ radula rasping algae off the rocks.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_6089",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>External fertilization releasing eggs and sperm into the water. Eggs develop into planktonic trochophore larvae that metamorphose and then settle as juvenile chitons.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_6090",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>One of three regional species in the genus, although only two have distributions in the Western Cape. Differs by means of flat lateral areas from <i>Callochiton dentatus </i>(Port Nolloth to Durban) and by both flat lateral areas and shell eyes not just restricted to the anterior third of the lateral areas<i> </i>from<i> Callochiton herberti </i>(Sodwana to Kosi Bay). The colour of this species is also very striking, separating it from the other two species.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_6091",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
